<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-4">
  <title>Resources for 9/4</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain how a <em>function</em> is a process that converts inputs into outputs.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain the definition of a function.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine whether or not a given <em>relation</em> is a function.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine the <em>domain</em>, <em>codomain</em>, and <em>range</em> of a given function.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-functions">
    <title>Video for Introduction to Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video introducing the concept of <em>functions</em>. Please watch the video and then go on to the next video and activities below.
    </p>

    <video youtube="BBzc4ewbLu8" />

    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-domain-codomain-range">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Domain, Codomain, &amp; Range</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on the <em>domain, codomain, &amp; range</em> of a function. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="T_X4fJzZJcY" />

    <problem>
      <title>Domain, Codomain, and Range of Functions</title>
      <p>
        For the following functions, use your common sense to determine a reasonable domain, codomain, and range.  Use a graphing utility if necessary.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x-2}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = \frac{2x-1}{x-3}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <tabular halign="right">
              <row>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>x</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>1</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">2</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">4</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">6</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor">7</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="minor"><m>f(x)</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>-2</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>-1</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">0</cell>
                <cell right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>The function with the following graph</p>
            <image>
            	<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="domain-range-graph-prep">
                <diagram dimensions="(300, 300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=cos(3*(x+2)/pi)+2</definition>
                  <definition>g(x)=-0.25*x^2+4.25</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-3,-3,6,5)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-2,1)"/>
                    <graph function="g" domain="(1,5)"/>
                    <point p="(-2,3)" stroke="blue" fill="white" />
                    <point p="(1,1)" stroke="blue" fill="white" />
                    <point p="(1,4)" stroke="blue" fill="blue" />
                    <point p="(5,-2)" stroke="blue" fill="blue" />
                  </coordinates>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-functions-relations">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Functions &amp; Relations</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on the distinction between <em>functions &amp; relations</em> of a function. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="chsC456Jvks" />

    <problem>
      <title>Functions &amp; Relations</title>
      <p>
        For each of the following relations, determine if it is a function.  Note that if the variables are <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, then <m>x</m> is the input and <m>y</m> is the output.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <tabular halign="right">
              <row>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>x</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>1</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">2</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">4</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">6</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor">7</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="minor"><m>f(x)</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>-2</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>-1</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">0</cell>
                <cell right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </li>
          <li>
            <tabular halign="right">
              <row>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>x</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"><m>1</m></cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">2</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">4</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">2</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor" right="minor">6</cell>
                <cell bottom="minor">7</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell right="minor"><m>f(x)</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>-2</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">5</cell>
                <cell right="minor"><m>-1</m></cell>
                <cell right="minor">0</cell>
                <cell right="minor">3</cell>
                <cell right="minor">4</cell>
                <cell>1</cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x+y^2=4</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2+y=4</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>The function with the following graph</p>
            <image>
            	<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="relation-function-1-prep">
                <diagram dimensions="(300, 300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=(1/tan(1.5*pi/4))*tan(pi*(x+2.5)/4)</definition>
                  <definition>g(x)=pi/(3*sqrt(2))*(x+1)^2-3*pi/(4*sqrt(2))-sqrt(2)+2</definition>
                  <definition>h(x)=-sec(pi*(x-1)/2)+2</definition>
                  <definition>k(x)=1/(x-2)</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-5,-3,6,5)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-4,-1)"/>
                    <graph function="g" domain="(-1,0.5)"/>
                    <graph function="h" domain="(0.5,2)"/>
                    <graph function="k" domain="(2,5)"/>
                    <line endpoints="((2,-3),(2,5))" infinite="yes" dash="8 8" stroke="black" />
                    <point p="(-4,-1)" stroke="blue" fill="blue" />
                    <point p="(-1,1)" stroke="blue" fill="white" />
                    <point p="(-1,g(-1))" stroke="blue" fill="white" />
                    <point p="(5,k(5))" stroke="blue" fill="blue" />
                  </coordinates>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>The function with the following graph</p>
            <image>
            	<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="relation-function-2-prep">
                <diagram dimensions="(300, 300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=sqrt(x+2)</definition>
                  <definition>g(x)=-sqrt(x+2)</definition>
                  <definition>h(x)=sqrt(-x+2)+2*sqrt(2)</definition>
                  <definition>k(x)=-sqrt(-x+2)+2*sqrt(2)</definition>
                  <definition></definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-8,-5,8,6)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-8,0)"/>
                    <graph function="g" />
                    <graph function="h" />
                    <graph function="k" domain="(0,2)"/>
                  </coordinates>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              One of the relations in #3 and #4 is a function, and one is not a function.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    For the relation that is a function, find a formula for the function.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    For the relation that is not a function, show how trying to solve for the formula of the function shows that it is not a function.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

